===Honorary degrees===
Cosby has received honorary degrees from more than a dozen colleges and universities:
* Honorary [[Doctor of Humane Letters]] degree from [[Boston University]], May 18, 2014<ref>{{cite web|title= BU to Confer Honorary Degree on Bill Cosby|url=http://www.bu.edu/today/2014/bu-to-confer-honorary-degree-on-bill-cosby/|date=|publisher=Boston University BU Today|accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>
* Honorary [[Doctor of Letters]] degree from [[Marquette University]], May 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title= Bill Cosby is Marquette University’s spring Commencement speaker|url= http://www.marquette.edu/omc/newscenter/recent.php?subaction=showfull&id=1368106200&archive=|date=|publisher=Marquette University Office of Marketing and Communication|accessdate=May 20, 2013}}</ref>
* Honorary [[Doctor of Humane Letters]] degree from [[Virginia Commonwealth University]], December 5, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title= VCU 40th Anniversary Events|url= http://www.40th.vcu.edu/events/billcosby.html|date=|publisher=Virginia Commonwealth University|accessdate=September 19, 2009}}</ref>
* Honorary [[Doctor of Humane Letters]] degree from [[Carnegie Mellon University]], May 20, 2007; he was also the [[Keynote|keynote speaker]] for the [[Graduation|commencement ceremony]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Commencement 2007: Celebrating Honors and Achievements|url= http://www.cmu.edu/homepage/beyond/2007/spring/commencement-2007.shtml|date=|publisher=Carnegie Mellon University|accessdate=September 19, 2009}}</ref>
* Honorary [[Doctor of Music]] degree from [[Berklee College of Music]], May 8, 2004.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Retiring College President Lee Eliot Berk and Bill Cosby Honored at Berklee College of Music's 2004 Commencement|publisher=Berklee College of Music|date=May 8, 2004|url=http://www.berklee.edu/commencement/2004/default.html|accessdate=September 19, 2009}}</ref> Cosby was also the host of the school's 60th Anniversary Concert in January 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title= Three Score: The Berklee 60th Anniversary Concert|url= http://www.berklee.edu/events/2006/01/60th.html|date=January 28, 2006|publisher= Berklee College of Music|accessdate=September 19, 2009}}</ref>
* Honorary [[Doctor of Humane Letters]] degree from [[Baylor University]], September 4, 2003, at the "Spirit Rally" for the Baylor and Central Texas communities.<ref>{{cite web|title= Bill Cosby Lifts Baylor, Waco Spirits At "Pep Rally"|url= http://www.baylor.edu/pr/news.php?action=story&story=5467|date= September 5, 2003|publisher= Baylor University|accessdate=September 19, 2009}}</ref>
* Honorary [[Doctor of Humane Letters]] degree from [[Yale University]], May 26, 2003.<ref>{{Cite journal|date= June 6, 2003|title=Honorary Degrees|journal=Yale Bulletin and Calendar|volume= 31|issue= 31|url= http://www.yale.edu/opa/arc-ybc/v31.n31/story103.html|accessdate=September 19, 2009}}</ref>
* Honorary Degree in 2003 presented by President [[William Harjo LoneFight]] from the [[Sisseton Wahpeton College]] on the Lake Traverse Reservation for his contributions to minority education.
* Honorary Doctorate from [[West Chester University of Pennsylvania]] during the 2003 graduation ceremony.
* Honorary Doctorate from [[Drew University]] during the 2002 graduation ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|title= Bill Cosby Commencement Speech 2002|url= https://vimeo.com/88475482|date=May 2002|publisher= Drew University|accessdate=March 29, 2015}}</ref>
* Honorary [[Doctor of Humane Letters]] degree from [[Haverford College]], May 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title= Honorary Degree Recipients|url= http://www.haverford.edu/commencement/files/honorarydegrees.pdf|date= July 7, 2009|publisher= Haverford College|accessdate=September 19, 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091008122800/http://www.haverford.edu/commencement/files/honorarydegrees.pdf| archivedate= October 8, 2009 | deadurl= no}}</ref>
* Honorary Degrees from [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]]<ref name="rpi_grad" /> and the [[University of Cincinnati]] in 2001.
* Honorary Doctorate from [[Amherst College]], May 1999. (Doctor of Humane Letters, ''honoris causa'')
* Honorary Doctorate from [[Colgate University]], May 22, 1999; he was also the keynote speaker for the commencement ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Cosby: Commencement Speaker|url=http://www.newswise.com/articles/bill-cosby-commencement-speaker1|accessdate=May 19, 2013|newspaper=Newswise|date=May 22, 1999}}</ref> 
* Honorary [[Doctor of Fine Arts]] degree from the [[University of Southern California]], May 8, 1998.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Joyous Day of Academic Celebration - USC's 115th Commencement, May 8, 1998 |url=http://www.usc.edu/uscnews/stories/3677.html|date=May 8, 1998|publisher=USC News|accessdate=March 27, 2012}}</ref>
* Cosby served as the [[Commencement speech|commencement speaker]]<ref>{{cite web|title= Commencement: Honorary Degrees|url= http://commencement.uconn.edu/history/speakers/1990s.html|date=May 18, 1996 |publisher= University of Connecticut|accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref> and received an Honorary [[Doctor of Fine Arts]] from the [[University of Connecticut]], May 18, 1996.<ref>{{cite web|title= Commencement: Honorary Degrees|url= http://digitalcommons.uconn.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1092&context=upub_commence|date=May 18, 1996 |publisher= University of Connecticut|accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref>
* Honorary [[Doctor of Humane Letters]] degree from [[Swarthmore College]], 1995.<ref>{{cite web|title=Past Speakers and Honorary Degree Recipients|url=http://www.swarthmore.edu/past-commencement/past-speakers-and-honorary-degree-recipients-(1888-2013).xml|accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>
* Honorary [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from the [[University of Pennsylvania]], 1990.<ref>{{cite web|title= Commencement: Honorary Degrees|url= http://www.upenn.edu/commencement/hist/hondegalph.html#C|date= |publisher= University of Pennsylvania|accessdate=September 19, 2009}}</ref> He also served as the [[Commencement speech|commencement speaker]] in May 1997.<ref>{{cite web|title= Commencement: Speakers Since 1938|url=http://www.upenn.edu/commencement/hist/speakers38.html|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|accessdate=September 19, 2009}}</ref>

